But whether or not a woman can get an abortion is complicated by a series of laws:

• A foundation law passed over a quarter century ago bans abortion, except for preserving the life or physical health of the woman, but an abortion is only permitted at a licensed hospital or clinic. Abortion is thereafter legal throughout the rest of the pregnancy if the doctor provides access to the prescription medication, RU486.

• The juvenile code of Marshall Island prohibits there to be procedures to abort first trimester pregnancy and/or perform an abortion under any circumstances unless such an abortion has been duly authorized by the court of appropriate jurisdiction or the Director of the Correctional Facility. A pregnant minor is therefore not allowed to voluntarily end up her pregnancy, even with parental consent.

• Offenders and delinquents defined in the juvenile rules law may be confined within a correctional institution at the order of the court of appropriate jurisdiction. But the same law also stipulates that a minor person above 12 years of age shall be confined at the Correctional Facility if he or she violates any law refuse to obey a lawful order. (JQD, 2002)
